            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The issue title kind of confused me. It sounds like the actual request here is: `--server \"foo\"` (where \"foo\" is a *name* as opposed to a *file* or *address*), should connect to the \"foo\" server. (LMK if I understood correctly.)\r\n\r\n> --server foo causes nvim to try and connect to a unix socket `foo` in the current directory.\r\n\r\n\r\nThis \"name\" feature currently hasn't been documented or fully developed, but it makes sense that a single \"name\" should be owned by a single server.\r\n\r\nThe reason for the `foo.<PID>.<COUNTER>` name on the filesystem is to give a hint about which process owns it. That's an implementation detail though.\r\n\r\n> but having multiple sockets for the same name & PID in `stdpath('run')` is a little odd to me.\r\n\r\nDo you mean same name and *different* PID? Or can you show an example.\r\n\r\n",
